{"title_page": "LineageOS", "text_new": "{{short description|Free and open-source operating system based on Android}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox OS\n| name = LineageOS\n| logo = LineageOS Wordmark.svg\n| logo_size = 200\n| screenshot = LineageOS 16.0 home screen.png\n| screenshot_size = 250px\n| caption = LineageOS 16.0 home screen\n| developer = LineageOS open-source community\n| programmed_in = [[C (programming language)|C]] (core), [[C++]] (some third party libraries), [[Java (programming language)|Java]] ([[User interface|UI]])\n| family = [[Unix-like]]\n<!-- Not really a release\n| released               = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2016|12|24}}\n-->| working_state = Active\n| source_model = [[Open-source software|Open source]]\n| latest release version = {{plainlist|\n* Official LineageOS 17.1,  based on [[Android 10]] (Q)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Changelog-24|title=Changelog-24|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org}}</ref>\n}}\n| marketing_target = [[Firmware]] replacement for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile devices\n| language = {{Collapsible list\n | title = Languages list\n | [[Arabic]]\n | [[Burmese language|Burmese]]\n | [[Catalan language|Catalan]]\n | [[Simplified Chinese language|Simplified Chinese]]\n | [[Traditional Chinese language|Traditional Chinese]]\n | [[Czech language|Czech]]\n | [[Danish language|Danish]]\n | [[Dutch language|Dutch]]\n | [[English language|English]]\n | [[Finnish language|Finnish]]\n | [[French language|French]]\n | [[German language|German]]\n | [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n | [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n | [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]\n | [[Italian language|Italian]]\n | [[Japanese language|Japanese]]\n | [[Kannada language|Kannada]]\n | [[Korean language|Korean]]\n | [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]]\n | [[Bahasa|Malay]]\n | [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]\n | [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]\n | [[Polish language|Polish]]\n | [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]\n | [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]\n | [[Russian language|Russian]]\n | [[Sinhala language|Sinhala]]\n | [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n | [[Swedish language|Swedish]]\n | [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n | [[Thai language|Thai]]\n | [[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n | [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]\n | [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]\n }}\n| updatemodel = [[Over-the-air programming|Over-the-air (OTA)]], ROM flashing\n| package_manager = [[Android application package|APK]]-based\n| supported_platforms = [[ARM architecture|arm, arm64]], [[x86]], [[x86-64]]\n| kernel_type = [[Monolithic kernel|Monolithic]] ([[Linux kernel|Linux]])\n| license = [[Apache_License#Version_2.0|Apache 2]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://github.com/LineageOS/android_vendor_lineage/blob/lineage-16.0/LICENSE | title = android_vendor_lineage_LICENSE  | work = LineageOS | accessdate = 31 March 2019}}</ref> [[MIT_License|MIT]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://github.com/LineageOS/www/blob/master/LICENSE | title = www_LICENSE at master \u00b7 LineageOS/www | work = LineageOS | accessdate = 31 March 2019}}</ref> and other licenses<ref>{{cite web | url = https://github.com/LineageOS/ | title = Other licenses can be viewed per repo on GitHub under NOTICE/LICENSE files | work = LineageOS | accessdate = 31 March 2019}}</ref>\n| preceded by = [[CyanogenMod]]\n[[CyanogenMod#Cyanogen_OS|CyanogenOS]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.lineageos.org}}\n| author = \n}}\n\n'''LineageOS''' is a [[Free and open-source software|free and open-source]] [[operating system]] for [[smartphone]]s, [[tablet computer]]s, and [[set-top box]]es, based on the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile platform. It is the successor to the custom ROM [[CyanogenMod]], from which it was [[fork (software)|forked]] in December 2016 when [[Cyanogen Inc.]] announced it was discontinuing development and shut down the infrastructure behind the project.<ref>{{cite news |last=Heater |first=Brian |date=24 December 2016 |title=After having its infrastructure shuttered, CyanogenMod will live on as Lineage |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/12/24/lineage/ |work=[[TechCrunch]] |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=24 December 2016 |title=A fork in the road |url=https://www.cyanogenmod.org/blog/a-fork-in-the-road |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225144318/https://www.cyanogenmod.org/blog/a-fork-in-the-road |archivedate=25 December 2016 |publisher=[[CyanogenMod]] |accessdate=26 December 2016 }}</ref> Since Cyanogen Inc. retained the rights to the Cyanogen name, the project rebranded its fork as LineageOS.<ref>{{cite news |last=Levy |first=Nat |date=26 December 2016 |title=Open-source Lineage project rises from Cyanogen's ashes as Android maker abruptly shuts down services |url=http://www.geekwire.com/2016/open-source-lineage-project-rises-cyanogens-ashes-android-maker-abruptly-shuts-services/ |work=[[GeekWire]] |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nLineageOS was officially launched on 24 December 2016, with the [[source code]] available on both [[GitHub]] and [[GitLab]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2016/12/cyanogen-inc-shuts-down-cyanogenmod-in-christmas-bloodbath/|title=Cyanogen Inc. shuts down CyanogenMod in Christmas bloodbath.|last=Gallagher|first=Sean Gallagher|date=27 December 2016|work=Ars Technica|accessdate=|publisher=Ars Technica}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://gitlab.com/LineageOS |title=LineageOS |website=GitLab.com |accessdate=2020-02-05}}</ref> As with all versions of Android, operating system releases are specific to a single model. Since its launch, LineageOS development builds are available for 109 phone models<ref name=\"hudson build targets\">{{Cite web|url= https://github.com/LineageOS/hudson/blob/master/lineage-build-targets |title= LineageOS/hudson build targets |date=24 February 2019 |website= GitHub |access-date= 2019-02-25}}</ref> with over 1.7 million active installs,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stats.lineageos.org/|title=LineageOS Statistics|date=2019-03-17|website=Stats.lineageos.org|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref> having doubled its user base in the months February\u2013March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.androidauthority.com/lineageos-one-million-users-one-plus-one-757895/|title=LineageOS now has one million users, OnePlus One is the most popular device|date=20 March 2017|website=Androidauthority.com|accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{main|CyanogenMod}}\n\n[[CyanogenMod]] (often abbreviated \"CM\") was a popular<ref name=\"userbase\" /> [[Open-source software|open-source]] [[operating system]] for [[smartphone]]s and [[tablet computer]]s, based on the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile platform. Although only a subset of total CyanogenMod users elected to report their use of the firmware,<ref>{{cite web|last=Soyars |first=Chris |date=21 March 2011 |url=http://www.cyanogenmod.org/blog/cmstats-what-it-is-and-why-you-should-opt-in |title=CM Stats explanation |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604144514/http://www.cyanogenmod.org/blog/cmstats-what-it-is-and-why-you-should-opt-in |archivedate= 4 June 2016 |accessdate=27 October 2011 }}</ref> as of 23 March 2015, some reports indicated over 50 million people running CyanogenMod on their phones.<ref name=\"userbase\">{{cite web|last1=Helft|first1=Miguel |title=Meet Cyanogen, The Startup That Wants To Steal Android From Google|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/miguelhelft/2015/03/23/meet-cyanogen-the-startup-that-wants-to-steal-android-from-google-2/|website=Forbes.com|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |author=CyanogenMod |user=CyanogenMod |date=12 January 2012 |title=CyanogenMod just passed 1 million active users. |number=157378138802888704 |url=https://twitter.com/CyanogenMod/status/157378138802888704 |link=no |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> It was also frequently used as a starting point by developers of other ROMs.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\nIn 2013, the founder, [[Steve Kondik]], obtained [[venture funding]] under the name Cyanogen Inc. to allow commercialization of the project.<ref name=\"newchapter\">{{cite web |url=https://github.com/lineageos |title=Lineage Android Distribution |publisher=LineageOS |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225133851/https://github.com/LineageOS |archivedate=25 December 2016 |accessdate=25 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Reed |first=Brad |date=18 September 2013 |title=With $7 million in funding, Cyanogen aims to take on Windows Phone |url=http://bgr.com/2013/09/18/cyanogen-venture-funding-7-million-dollars/ |work=[[Boy Genius Report]] |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> In his view, the company did not capitalize on the project's success and in 2016 he either left or was forced out<ref name=\"nov2016-update\">{{cite web |last=Tal |first=Lior |date=30 November 2016 |title=Update on Cyanogen |url=https://cyngn.com/blog/update-on-cyanogen |publisher=Cyanogen Inc. |accessdate=24 January 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227202203/https://cyngn.com/blog/update-on-cyanogen |archivedate=27 December 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ruddock |first=David |date=28 November 2016 |title=Cyanogen Inc. will shutter Seattle office by end of year, more layoffs happening, Kondik could be out |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2016/11/28/cyanogen-inc-will-shutter-seattle-office-by-end-of-year-more-layoffs-happening-kondik-could-be-out |work=Android Police |accessdate=24 January 2017 |quote=Kondik was removed from the company's board, allegedly}}</ref> as part of a corporate [[restructuring|restructure]] which involved a change of [[Chief executive officer|CEO]], closure of offices and projects, and cessation of services.<ref name=\"cm-dnsloss\">{{cite tweet |author=CyanogenMod |user=CyanogenMod |date=25 December 2016 |title=UPDATE: As of this morning we have lost DNS and Gerrit is now offline&nbsp;\u2014 with little doubt as a reaction to our blog post yesterday. Goodbye |number=813086249506349056 |url=https://twitter.com/CyanogenMod/status/813086249506349056 |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> The code itself, being both [[Open-source software|open source]] and popular, was quickly [[fork (software)|forked]] under the new name LineageOS and efforts began to resume development as a community project.\n\nCyanogenMod offered a number of features and options not available in the official [[firmware]] distributed by most mobile device vendors. Features supported by CyanogenMod included native [[Skin (computing)|theme]] support,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyanogenmod.org/features/themes-support |title=Themes Support |publisher=CyanogenMod |date=19 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021081516/http://www.cyanogenmod.org/features/themes-support |archivedate=21 October 2016 |accessdate=30 September 2013 }}</ref> [[FLAC]] audio codec support, a large [[Access Point Name]] list, ''Privacy Guard'' (per-application [[Android (operating system)#Application security|permission]] management application), support for [[tethering]] over common interfaces, CPU [[overclocking]] and other performance enhancements, root access, soft buttons and other \"tablet tweaks,\" toggles in the notification pull-down (such as [[Wi-Fi]], [[Bluetooth]] and [[satellite navigation]]), and other interface enhancements. Many of the features from CyanogenMod were later integrated into the official Android code base. CyanogenMod's developers said that it did not contain [[spyware]] or [[bloatware]].<ref name=\"carrieriq\">{{cite web|url=http://www.computer-howto.com/2011/12/cyanogenmod-promises-include-apps-carrier-iq/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419085814/http://www.virtualizationhowto.com/2011/12/cyanogenmod-promises-include-apps-carrier-iq/|archive-date=19 April 2016|title=Cyanogenmod promises to never include apps like Carrier IQ|publisher=Computer-Howto|date=5 December 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://unleashthephones.com/2012/07/06/video-cyanogenmod-founder-steve-kondik-talks-android/ |title=Video: CyanogenMod founder Steve Kondik talks Android |website=UnleashThePhones.com |date=6 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130205051231/http://unleashthephones.com/2012/07/06/video-cyanogenmod-founder-steve-kondik-talks-android/ |archivedate= 5 February 2013 |accessdate=27 January 2013 }}</ref> CyanogenMod was also said to perform better and be more reliable than official firmware releases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyanogenmod.org/about |title=About |publisher=CyanogenMod.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222052026/https://www.cyanogenmod.org/about |archivedate=22 December 2016 |accessdate=27 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nLike CyanogenMod, the LineageOS project is developed by many device-specific maintainers and uses [[Gerrit (software)|Gerrit]] for its [[code review]] process. It also retained the old versioning format (for example, Android 7.1 is LineageOS 14.1). \n\nPrior to the official launch of LineageOS, many developers from [[XDA Developers|XDA]] had already developed unofficial versions of LineageOS from the source code.\n\n* On 22 January 2017, the first 14.1 and 13.0 official builds started to be made available, following the official announcement in a blog post.<ref name=\"build-prep\" />\n* On 11 February 2018, the 13.0 builds were stopped,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://review.lineageos.org/#/c/206008/|title=Gerrit Code Review|website=review.lineageos.org|access-date=2018-02-13}}</ref> while the source code remains available and security fixes are still accepted on Gerrit.\n* On 26 February 2018, the first 15.1 official builds started to be available on certain devices, following official announcement in a blog post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lineageos.org/Changelog-16/|title=Changelog 16 - Smart Styles, Treble is trouble and Omfg Oreo|last=LineageOS|website=www.lineageos.org|access-date=2018-02-25}}</ref> The 14.1 versions of Lineage OS were to remain in active development, but without feature advancements.\n* On 24 February 2019, the 14.1 builds were stopped and 15.1 builds moved to a weekly cadence<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://review.lineageos.org/c/LineageOS/hudson/+/242408|title=Prepare for 16.0|website=review.lineageos.org|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref>\n* On 1 March 2019, the first 16.0 official builds started to be available, following official announcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Changelog-22/|title=Changelog 22 - Pushing Pie, Bracing Builds and Careful Calculator|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> The 15.1 branch remains in active development, but without feature advancements.\n* On 28 February 2020, the 15.1 builds were stopped in preparation for the 17.1 release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/LineageOS/hudson/commit/4838aba0b3e9a71f0e7e07f9901c6ed81ea6fd80|title=RIP Oreo|website=github.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* On 1 April 2020, the first 17.1 builds started to be available, following official announcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Changelog-24/|title=Changelog 24|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The 16.0 builds are moved to a weekly cadence while the branch remains in active development, but without feature advancements.\n\nAll the released builds are signed with LineageOS' private keys.<ref name=\"build-prep\">{{cite web|url=http://lineageos.org/Update-and-Build-Prep/|title=Update & Build Prep|last=OS|first=Lineage|website=Lineageos.org|access-date=2017-01-21}}</ref>\n\nBuilds were released on a weekly basis until 12 November 2018, when the release cycle for devices has changed: the latest LineageOS branch is built daily, with devices receiving a \"nightly\" OTA update, while devices on the older branch are were moved to a weekly release cycle.<ref name=\"Release Cycle\">{{cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Changelog-21/|title=Changelog 21 - Nightlies Now, Improved Infrastructure and Precious Pie}}</ref>\n\n==Community==\nLineageOS allows the community to get involved with the development in various ways. [[Gerrit (software)|Gerrit]] is used for the code review process of both the operating system and the infrastructure.\n\nThe wiki, containing information regarding installation, support, and development of LineageOS, is also open to contributions through Gerrit. Other Lineage platforms include Crowdin for managing translations, [[GitLab|Gitlab Issues]] for bug tracking, and a stats page, which displays the number of active installations from users which opt-in to report this statistic. There is also an official [[Reddit|subreddit]], r/lineageos, and two [[Internet Relay Chat|IRC channels]] hosted on [[Freenode]] (''#lineageos'' and ''#lineageos-dev'').\n\nThe XDA Developers forums have been used by members of the Lineage community since the first inception of the software, many devices are left unsupported by official releases so community members develop their own Unofficial-ROMs that allow older phones to use Lineage. These unofficial releases are often bundled with software intended to aid the user's experience that would otherwise be unseen in an official release. They also come with known bugs and security issues that may not be seen in official releases.\n\nDuring August 2017 the LineageOS team held a Summer Survey<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lineageos.org/Summer-Survey/|title=Summer Survey|last=LineageOS|website=Lineageos.org|access-date=2017-10-25}}</ref> in which they asked users for feedback to improve the development of the operating system. The results were published<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lineageos.org/Summer-Survey-Results/|title=Summer Survey - Results|last=LineageOS|website=Lineageos.org|access-date=2017-10-25}}</ref> in October and, according to the team, they used the gathered data to improve the upcoming LineageOS 15 release. The second Summer Survey was conducted in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Summer-Survey-2/|title=Summer Survey 2 - Attack of the feedbacks|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org|access-date=2018-09-09}}</ref>\n\nAs a response to one of the main suggestions received during their first public survey, LineageOS launched a section on their blog titled \"LineageOS Engineering Blog\" where Lineage maintainers and developers can contribute articles discussing advanced technical information pertaining to Android development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Trust-me/|title=Trust me, I'm an engineer|date=12 June 2018|website=LineageOS|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nLineageOS is also known for posting a \"regularly irregular review\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lineageos.org/Changelog-13/|title=Changelog 13 - Wonderful Webviews, Pedantic Permissions and Disappearing Dates|last=LineageOS|website=Lineageos.org|access-date=2017-10-25}}</ref> on its blog in which the active development of the work is discussed.\n\n==Version history==\n{{See also|Android version history|CyanogenMod#History and development}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible\"\n|+\n|-\n! Version !! AOSP version\n!First build release date!! Last build release date\n!Support\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" {{Version|o|13.0}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 6.0.1<br />(Marshmallow)\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2016|12|20}} as CM<br />{{dts|format=dmy|2017|1|22}} as LOS\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2018|2|11}}\n|Unsupported\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" {{Version|o|14.1|show=}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 7.1.2 <br />(Nougat)\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2016|11|9}} as CM<br />{{dts|format=dmy|2017|1|22}} as LOS\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2019|2|24}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/LineageOS/hudson/commit/b8cf20218fd7676d7904152531e0f1cacead740f|title=Prepare for 16.0 \u00b7 LineageOS/hudson@b8cf202|website=GitHub|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref>\n|Unsupported\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" {{Version|o|15.1}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 8.1.0 <br />(Oreo)\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2018|2|26}}  \n|{{dts|format=dmy|2020|2|28}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/LineageOS/hudson/commit/4838aba0b3e9a71f0e7e07f9901c6ed81ea6fd80|title=RIP Oreo \u00b7 LineageOS/hudson@4838aba|website=Github|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n|Unsupported\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" {{Version|co|16.0}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 9.0.0 <br />(Pie)\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2019|3|1}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://review.lineageos.org/c/LineageOS/hudson/+/241918|title=The real lineage-16.0 ship commit}}</ref>\n| (Current)\n|Supported\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" {{Version|c|17.1}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 10 <br />\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2020|4|1}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Changelog-24|title=Changelog 24}}</ref>\n| (Current)\n|Supported\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" | <small>{{Version|l|show=111101}}</small>\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Preinstalled apps==\nLineageOS includes many essential and useful apps, but like its predecessor, CyanogenMod, it is free from unnecessary software often pre-installed by a phone's manufacturer or carrier that is considered to be [[bloatware]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://in.pcmag.com/lineage-os/112389/feature/how-to-install-lineage-os-on-your-smartphone |title=How to: Install Lineage OS on your smartphone |newspaper=In.pcmag.com |date=7 February 2017|author=Siddharth Chauhan|quote=As far as user interface goes, Lineage OS presents a clean and bloatware free stock Vanilla Android experience but still has some tricks up its sleeve. |accessdate= 20 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=carrieriq/>\n\n'''Current'''\n\n* AudioFX \u2013 Audio optimizer with presets to alter the listening experience.\n* Browser \u2013 A lightweight browser that relies on the System Webview, for low-end devices, also known as Jelly.\n* Calculator \u2013 which resembles a four-function calculator and offers some more advanced functions.\n* Calendar \u2013 Calendar functionality with Day, Week, Month, Year or Agenda views.\n* Camera \u2013 Dependent on device specification will take video or photos, including panoramic. It can also be used to read QR codes. This app is also known as Snap.\n* Clock \u2013 World clock, countdown timer, stopwatch and alarms.\n* Contacts \u2013 Phonebook for numbers and email addresses.\n* cLock - A weather widget.\n* Email \u2013 Email client that handles POP3, IMAP and Exchange.\n* Files \u2013 A simple file manager to move, copy and rename files on internal storage or SD card.\n* FlipFlap \u2013 An app for smart flip covers, only included on select devices.\n* FM Radio - An app for listening to FM radio broadcasts, included on devices with an FM tuner.\n* Gallery \u2013 Organize photos and videos into a timeline or albums for easy viewing.\n* Messaging \u2013An MMS/[[SMS]] messaging app.\n* Music \u2013 A simple music player, also known as Eleven.\n* Phone \u2013 for making calls: includes speed dial, phone number lookups and call blocking.\n* Recorder \u2013 A screen and/or sound recorder.\n* Trebuchet \u2013 A customizable launcher.\n* Terminal - A simple and standard terminal app.\n\n'''Former''' \n\n* Gello - A browser based on Chromium and developed by CyanogenMod. This app is now replaced by Jelly. \n* Yahoo Weather Provider - A weather provider\n* WeatherUnderground Weather Provider - A weather provider\n* Themes - Originally an app by itself, now integrated into the settings app.\n\nAlthough they are not included in LineageOS as such due to legal issues,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/09/24/google-hits-android-rom-modder-with-a-cease-and-desist-letter/|title=Google hits Android ROM modder with a cease-and-desist letter|work=Engadget|access-date=2017-10-25}}</ref> users can flash the normal Google apps, including the Google Play Store and Play Apps, with a [[Zip (file format)|Zip package]], usually referred to as ''gapps'', while installing LineageOS.\n\n==Unique features==\nLineageOS offers several features that [[Android (operating system)#AOSP|Android Open Source Project]] (AOSP) does not include. Some of these features are:\n\n==== Customization features ====\n\n* Button customization \u2013 Set custom location for buttons on the navigation bar, or enable on-screen buttons for devices with hardware buttons.\n* Custom Quick-Setting tiles \u2013 Quick Setting Tiles such as \"Caffeine\" preventing the device from sleeping, enabling/disabling Heads Up notifications, \"Ambient Display\" and \"ADB over network\" are present to easily toggle frequently accessed settings.\n* LiveDisplay \u2013 Adjust color temperature for the time of day.\n* Lock screen customization \u2013 The lock screen allows all sorts of customizations, including media cover art, a music visualizer, and double-tap to sleep.\n* Styles \u2013 Set a global dark or light theme mode and customize accent colors. This functionality can also be managed automatically by the system based on wallpaper or time of day (in line with LiveDisplay).\n* System Profiles \u2013 Enable or disable common settings based on the selected profile (For example, a \"Home\" profile and a \"Work\" profile). The profile can be selected either manually or through the use of a \"trigger\", such as upon connecting to a specific WiFi access point, connecting to a Bluetooth device, or tapping an [[Near-field communication|NFC]] tag.\n*Custom pattern sizes \u2013 In addition to Android's 3x3 pattern size, a 4x4, 5x5 or 6x6 size can be used.\n\n==== Security & privacy features ====\n\n* PIN scramble \u2013 For users securing their device with a [[Personal identification number|PIN]], the layout can be scrambled each time the device locks to make it difficult for people to figure out your lock by looking over your shoulder.\n* Privacy guard \u2013 Allow the user to fine-tune what permissions are granted to each application. For some permissions, it's possible to set a manual approval each time the permission is requested. It's also possible to find out how often apps use a specific permission. This feature was removed in the 17.1 branch in favor of an equivalent \"permission controller\" based on an hidden AOSP feature.\n* Protected Apps \u2013 Hide specific apps behind a secure lock. This works hand-in-hand with Trebuchet; the app's icon is removed from the launcher, and \"secure folders\" can be created to easily access these applications. A pattern is used to lock these apps.\n* Some \"sensitive numbers\", such as abuse support numbers, are not included in the call log for privacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Changelog-10/|title=Changelog 10 - Sensitive numbers and our CVE Tracker|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org}}</ref>\n* Trust - helps to keep the device secure and protects privacy.\n\n==== Developers & power user features ====\n\n* LineageSDK \u2013 a set of APIs for app developers to integrate their apps with LineageOS specific features such as System Profiles, Styles and Weather.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Introducing-the-LineageSDK/|title=Introducing the LineageSDK|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref>\n*Lineage Recovery - an AOSP-based recovery for devices with an A/B type system.\n* (Optional) Root \u2013 Permit apps to function with [[Superuser|root access]] to perform advanced tasks. This requires flashing from Recovery either LineageOS's root add-on or a third-party implementation such as Magisk or SuperSU.\n* Telephone call recorder, not available in all countries, due to legal restrictions.\n* Weather providers \u2013 Display the weather in widgets or apps using a weather provider. This functionality is not included by default; a weather provider must be downloaded from the LineageOS Downloads website. App developers can create both providers and consumers of weather data.\n\n==Trust interface==\nAs LineageOS evolved through development, the Trust interface was introduced for all the LineageOS 15.1 builds released since 12 June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Trust-me/|title=Trust me, I'm an engineer|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org}}</ref> The interface can be found on supported devices under Security and Privacy tab under the Settings option, and enables the user to \"get an overview of the status of core security features and explanations on how to act to make sure the device is secure and the data is private\".\n\nAdditionally, while carrying out any action on the device, the trust icon is displayed, notifying the user that the action is safe.\n\n==Supported devices==\nThe number of devices supported by LineageOS increases with time, being 105 for v15.1 and v16 {{As of|2019|8|25|lc=y|df=US}}.<ref name=\"hudson build targets\"/><ref name=\"devices\">{{cite web|url= http://wiki.lineageos.org/devices/ |title= Devices |website= LineageOS Wiki |access-date= 2019-11-23 }}</ref> Official builds on currently supported development branches are labeled as either \"nightly\", \"weekly\", or \"monthly\". For the first two months of the project, parallel experimental builds were also produced, allowing in-place upgrades from previous CyanogenMod installations and easing migration to LineageOS.<ref name=\"devices\"/><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://download.lineageos.org|title=LineageOS Downloads|access-date=24 January 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126175103/https://download.lineageos.org/|archivedate=26 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://lineageos.org/Update-and-Build-Prep/|title=Update & Build Prep|date=20 January 2017|newspaper=LineageOS|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |last=Rigg |first=Jamie |date=24 January 2017 |title=The first builds of CyanogenMod successor LineageOS are out |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/01/24/cyanogenmod-lineageos/ |work=[[Engadget]] |accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism and reception  ==\n===2018 April Fools' prank ===\nLineageOS was criticized for a deceptive [[April Fools' Day|April Fool's]] prank included with some April 2018 builds.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.androidpolice.com/2018/04/05/dont-freak-lineageos-bad-late-april-fools-joke-latest-builds/|title=Don't freak out: LineageOS has a very bad and very late April Fools' joke in latest builds|date=2018-04-05|work=Android Police|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first week of April 2018 LineageOS released new builds with the \"LOSGenuine\" prank that informed unaware users of the software possibly being counterfeit via a persistent notification (which could not be disabled unless the user ran the following command in a root shell):\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"shell\">\nsetprop persist.lineage.nofool true \n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nWhen the notification was tapped, the software claimed that the device was \"uncertified\" and needed to mine \"LOSCoins\", which were a virtual currency and could not actually be spent. Affected builds also had a preinstalled \"Wallet\" app that showed the current balance of LOSCoins.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nMany users mistook the prank for actual [[malware]], and others reportedly found it to be in \"poor taste\". It was especially criticized for being too \"late\" for an April Fool's joke, since many users didn't receive the update until days later, making the jest less obvious. On 10 April 2018, LineageOS team director ''ciwrl'' issued an official apology for the deceptive prank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/An-April-Apology/|title=An April Apology|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.androidpolice.com/2018/04/10/lineageos-apologises-late-bad-taste-april-fools-joke/|title=LineageOS apologizes for late and 'bad taste' April Fools' joke|date=2018-04-10|work=Android Police|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Forks==\n[[Replicant (operating system)|Replicant]] is a completely free software variant of LineageOS, with all kernel blobs and non-free drivers removed.\n\nAs a response to the refusal for several reasons of support for signature spoofing in official builds,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://review.lineageos.org/#/c/195284/|title=Gerrit Code Review|website=review.lineageos.org|access-date=2018-02-13}}</ref> a LineageOS fork with [[microG]]<ref name=\"microG\">\"[https://microg.org ''microG''] provides a free version of the set of APIs equivalent to Google\u2019s proprietary core libraries and applications.\"</ref> services included, known as \"LineageOS for microG\", was created. The project ships custom builds of LineageOS with the required patch and native [[F-Droid]] support, bundled with the MicroG project's [[free software|free]] re-implementation of proprietary [[Google mobile services|Gapps]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/LineageOS-Ableger-vermeidet-Google-Code-3879358.html|title=LineageOS-Ableger vermeidet Google-Code|first=heise|last=online|website=heise online}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gearallnews.com/what-is-microg-how-to-install-microg/|title=What is MicroG? How to Install MicroG?|date=26 November 2017|publisher=}}</ref> In other respects it follows upstream, shipping OTA updates every seven days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lineage.microg.org/|title=LineageOS for microG, FAQ}}</ref>\n\n[[/e/ (operating system)|/e/]] is a fork of LineageOS created by [[Ga\u00ebl Duval]] that is intended to be \"free from [[Google]]\". It replaces [[Google Play Services]] with MicroG, a [[free and open-source]] implementation of Google [[Application programming interface|APIs]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lemondeinformatique.fr/actualites/lire-eelo-l-os-mobile-open-source-de-gael-duval-sort-en-beta-72898.html|title=Eelo : l'OS mobile open source de Ga\u00ebl Duval sort en b\u00eata - Le Monde Informatique|last=Filippone|first=Dominique|date=September 19, 2018|website=LeMondeInformatique|language=fr|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Android rooting]]\n* [[Comparison of mobile operating systems]]\n* [[List of custom Android firmware]]\n* [[List of free and open-source Android applications]]\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.lineageos.org}}\n\n{{Android}}\n{{Linux-distro}}\n{{Mobile operating systems}}\n\n[[Category:Custom Android firmware]]\n[[Category:Embedded Linux distributions]]\n[[Category:Free mobile software]]\n[[Category:Software forks]]\n[[Category:Linux distributions without systemd]]\n[[Category:Android forks]]\n[[Category:2016 software]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Free and open-source operating system based on Android}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox OS\n| name = LineageOS\n| logo = LineageOS Wordmark.svg\n| logo_size = 200\n| screenshot = LineageOS 16.0 home screen.png\n| screenshot_size = 250px\n| caption = LineageOS 16.0 home screen\n| developer = LineageOS open-source community\n| programmed_in = [[C (programming language)|C]] (core), [[C++]] (some third party libraries), [[Java (programming language)|Java]] ([[User interface|UI]])\n| family = [[Unix-like]]\n<!-- Not really a release\n| released               = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2016|12|24}}\n-->| working_state = Active\n| source_model = [[Open-source software|Open source]]\n| latest release version = {{plainlist|\n* Official LineageOS 17.1,  based on [[Android 10]] (Q)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Changelog-24|title=Changelog-24|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org}}</ref>\n}}\n| marketing_target = [[Firmware]] replacement for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile devices\n| language = {{Collapsible list\n | title = Languages list\n | [[Arabic]]\n | [[Burmese language|Burmese]]\n | [[Catalan language|Catalan]]\n | [[Simplified Chinese language|Simplified Chinese]]\n | [[Traditional Chinese language|Traditional Chinese]]\n | [[Czech language|Czech]]\n | [[Danish language|Danish]]\n | [[Dutch language|Dutch]]\n | [[English language|English]]\n | [[Finnish language|Finnish]]\n | [[French language|French]]\n | [[German language|German]]\n | [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n | [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n | [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]\n | [[Italian language|Italian]]\n | [[Japanese language|Japanese]]\n | [[Kannada language|Kannada]]\n | [[Korean language|Korean]]\n | [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]]\n | [[Bahasa|Malay]]\n | [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]\n | [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]\n | [[Polish language|Polish]]\n | [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]\n | [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]\n | [[Russian language|Russian]]\n | [[Sinhala language|Sinhala]]\n | [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n | [[Swedish language|Swedish]]\n | [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n | [[Thai language|Thai]]\n | [[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n | [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]\n | [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]\n }}\n| updatemodel = [[Over-the-air programming|Over-the-air (OTA)]], ROM flashing\n| package_manager = [[Android application package|APK]]-based\n| supported_platforms = [[ARM architecture|arm, arm64]], [[x86]], [[x86-64]]\n| kernel_type = [[Monolithic kernel|Monolithic]] ([[Linux kernel|Linux]])\n| license = [[Apache_License#Version_2.0|Apache 2]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://github.com/LineageOS/android_vendor_lineage/blob/lineage-16.0/LICENSE | title = android_vendor_lineage_LICENSE  | work = LineageOS | accessdate = 31 March 2019}}</ref> [[MIT_License|MIT]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://github.com/LineageOS/www/blob/master/LICENSE | title = www_LICENSE at master \u00b7 LineageOS/www | work = LineageOS | accessdate = 31 March 2019}}</ref> and other licenses<ref>{{cite web | url = https://github.com/LineageOS/ | title = Other licenses can be viewed per repo on GitHub under NOTICE/LICENSE files | work = LineageOS | accessdate = 31 March 2019}}</ref>\n| preceded by = [[CyanogenMod]]\n[[CyanogenMod#Cyanogen_OS|CyanogenOS]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.lineageos.org}}\n| author = \n}}\n\n'''LineageOS''' is a [[Free and open-source software|free and open-source]] [[operating system]] for [[smartphone]]s, [[tablet computer]]s, and [[set-top box]]es, based on the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile platform. It is the successor to the custom ROM [[CyanogenMod]], from which it was [[fork (software)|forked]] in December 2016 when [[Cyanogen Inc.]] announced it was discontinuing development and shut down the infrastructure behind the project.<ref>{{cite news |last=Heater |first=Brian |date=24 December 2016 |title=After having its infrastructure shuttered, CyanogenMod will live on as Lineage |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/12/24/lineage/ |work=[[TechCrunch]] |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=24 December 2016 |title=A fork in the road |url=https://www.cyanogenmod.org/blog/a-fork-in-the-road |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225144318/https://www.cyanogenmod.org/blog/a-fork-in-the-road |archivedate=25 December 2016 |publisher=[[CyanogenMod]] |accessdate=26 December 2016 }}</ref> Since Cyanogen Inc. retained the rights to the Cyanogen name, the project rebranded its fork as LineageOS.<ref>{{cite news |last=Levy |first=Nat |date=26 December 2016 |title=Open-source Lineage project rises from Cyanogen's ashes as Android maker abruptly shuts down services |url=http://www.geekwire.com/2016/open-source-lineage-project-rises-cyanogens-ashes-android-maker-abruptly-shuts-services/ |work=[[GeekWire]] |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nLineageOS was officially launched on 24 December 2016, with the [[source code]] available on both [[GitHub]] and [[GitLab]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2016/12/cyanogen-inc-shuts-down-cyanogenmod-in-christmas-bloodbath/|title=Cyanogen Inc. shuts down CyanogenMod in Christmas bloodbath.|last=Gallagher|first=Sean Gallagher|date=27 December 2016|work=Ars Technica|accessdate=|publisher=Ars Technica}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://gitlab.com/LineageOS |title=LineageOS |website=GitLab.com |accessdate=2020-02-05}}</ref> As with all versions of Android, operating system releases are specific to a single model. Since its launch, LineageOS development builds are available for 109 phone models<ref name=\"hudson build targets\">{{Cite web|url= https://github.com/LineageOS/hudson/blob/master/lineage-build-targets |title= LineageOS/hudson build targets |date=24 February 2019 |website= GitHub |access-date= 2019-02-25}}</ref> with over 1.7 million active installs,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stats.lineageos.org/|title=LineageOS Statistics|date=2019-03-17|website=Stats.lineageos.org|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref> having doubled its user base in the months February\u2013March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.androidauthority.com/lineageos-one-million-users-one-plus-one-757895/|title=LineageOS now has one million users, OnePlus One is the most popular device|date=20 March 2017|website=Androidauthority.com|accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{main|CyanogenMod}}\n\n[[CyanogenMod]] (often abbreviated \"CM\") was a popular<ref name=\"userbase\" /> [[Open-source software|open-source]] [[operating system]] for [[smartphone]]s and [[tablet computer]]s, based on the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile platform. Although only a subset of total CyanogenMod users elected to report their use of the firmware,<ref>{{cite web|last=Soyars |first=Chris |date=21 March 2011 |url=http://www.cyanogenmod.org/blog/cmstats-what-it-is-and-why-you-should-opt-in |title=CM Stats explanation |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604144514/http://www.cyanogenmod.org/blog/cmstats-what-it-is-and-why-you-should-opt-in |archivedate= 4 June 2016 |accessdate=27 October 2011 }}</ref> as of 23 March 2015, some reports indicated over 50 million people running CyanogenMod on their phones.<ref name=\"userbase\">{{cite web|last1=Helft|first1=Miguel |title=Meet Cyanogen, The Startup That Wants To Steal Android From Google|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/miguelhelft/2015/03/23/meet-cyanogen-the-startup-that-wants-to-steal-android-from-google-2/|website=Forbes.com|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |author=CyanogenMod |user=CyanogenMod |date=12 January 2012 |title=CyanogenMod just passed 1 million active users. |number=157378138802888704 |url=https://twitter.com/CyanogenMod/status/157378138802888704 |link=no |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> It was also frequently used as a starting point by developers of other ROMs.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\nIn 2013, the founder, [[Steve Kondik]], obtained [[venture funding]] under the name Cyanogen Inc. to allow commercialization of the project.<ref name=\"newchapter\">{{cite web |url=https://github.com/lineageos |title=Lineage Android Distribution |publisher=LineageOS |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225133851/https://github.com/LineageOS |archivedate=25 December 2016 |accessdate=25 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Reed |first=Brad |date=18 September 2013 |title=With $7 million in funding, Cyanogen aims to take on Windows Phone |url=http://bgr.com/2013/09/18/cyanogen-venture-funding-7-million-dollars/ |work=[[Boy Genius Report]] |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> In his view, the company did not capitalize on the project's success and in 2016 he either left or was forced out<ref name=\"nov2016-update\">{{cite web |last=Tal |first=Lior |date=30 November 2016 |title=Update on Cyanogen |url=https://cyngn.com/blog/update-on-cyanogen |publisher=Cyanogen Inc. |accessdate=24 January 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227202203/https://cyngn.com/blog/update-on-cyanogen |archivedate=27 December 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ruddock |first=David |date=28 November 2016 |title=Cyanogen Inc. will shutter Seattle office by end of year, more layoffs happening, Kondik could be out |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2016/11/28/cyanogen-inc-will-shutter-seattle-office-by-end-of-year-more-layoffs-happening-kondik-could-be-out |work=Android Police |accessdate=24 January 2017 |quote=Kondik was removed from the company's board, allegedly}}</ref> as part of a corporate [[restructuring|restructure]] which involved a change of [[Chief executive officer|CEO]], closure of offices and projects, and cessation of services.<ref name=\"cm-dnsloss\">{{cite tweet |author=CyanogenMod |user=CyanogenMod |date=25 December 2016 |title=UPDATE: As of this morning we have lost DNS and Gerrit is now offline&nbsp;\u2014 with little doubt as a reaction to our blog post yesterday. Goodbye |number=813086249506349056 |url=https://twitter.com/CyanogenMod/status/813086249506349056 |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> The code itself, being both [[Open-source software|open source]] and popular, was quickly [[fork (software)|forked]] under the new name LineageOS and efforts began to resume development as a community project.\n\nCyanogenMod offered a number of features and options not available in the official [[firmware]] distributed by most mobile device vendors. Features supported by CyanogenMod included native [[Skin (computing)|theme]] support,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyanogenmod.org/features/themes-support |title=Themes Support |publisher=CyanogenMod |date=19 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021081516/http://www.cyanogenmod.org/features/themes-support |archivedate=21 October 2016 |accessdate=30 September 2013 }}</ref> [[FLAC]] audio codec support, a large [[Access Point Name]] list, ''Privacy Guard'' (per-application [[Android (operating system)#Application security|permission]] management application), support for [[tethering]] over common interfaces, CPU [[overclocking]] and other performance enhancements, root access, soft buttons and other \"tablet tweaks,\" toggles in the notification pull-down (such as [[Wi-Fi]], [[Bluetooth]] and [[satellite navigation]]), and other interface enhancements. Many of the features from CyanogenMod were later integrated into the official Android code base. CyanogenMod's developers said that it did not contain [[spyware]] or [[bloatware]].<ref name=\"carrieriq\">{{cite web|url=http://www.computer-howto.com/2011/12/cyanogenmod-promises-include-apps-carrier-iq/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419085814/http://www.virtualizationhowto.com/2011/12/cyanogenmod-promises-include-apps-carrier-iq/|archive-date=19 April 2016|title=Cyanogenmod promises to never include apps like Carrier IQ|publisher=Computer-Howto|date=5 December 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://unleashthephones.com/2012/07/06/video-cyanogenmod-founder-steve-kondik-talks-android/ |title=Video: CyanogenMod founder Steve Kondik talks Android |website=UnleashThePhones.com |date=6 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130205051231/http://unleashthephones.com/2012/07/06/video-cyanogenmod-founder-steve-kondik-talks-android/ |archivedate= 5 February 2013 |accessdate=27 January 2013 }}</ref> CyanogenMod was also said to perform better and be more reliable than official firmware releases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyanogenmod.org/about |title=About |publisher=CyanogenMod.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222052026/https://www.cyanogenmod.org/about |archivedate=22 December 2016 |accessdate=27 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nLike CyanogenMod, the LineageOS project is developed by many device-specific maintainers and uses [[Gerrit (software)|Gerrit]] for its [[code review]] process. It also retained the old versioning format (for example, Android 7.1 is LineageOS 14.1). \n\nPrior to the official launch of LineageOS, many developers from [[XDA Developers|XDA]] had already developed unofficial versions of LineageOS from the source code.\n\n* On 22 January 2017, the first 14.1 and 13.0 official builds started to be made available, following the official announcement in a blog post.<ref name=\"build-prep\" />\n* On 11 February 2018, the 13.0 builds were stopped,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://review.lineageos.org/#/c/206008/|title=Gerrit Code Review|website=review.lineageos.org|access-date=2018-02-13}}</ref> while the source code remains available and security fixes are still accepted on Gerrit.\n* On 26 February 2018, the first 15.1 official builds started to be available on certain devices, following official announcement in a blog post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lineageos.org/Changelog-16/|title=Changelog 16 - Smart Styles, Treble is trouble and Omfg Oreo|last=LineageOS|website=www.lineageos.org|access-date=2018-02-25}}</ref> The 14.1 versions of Lineage OS were to remain in active development, but without feature advancements.\n* On 24 February 2019, the 14.1 builds were stopped and 15.1 builds moved to a weekly cadence<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://review.lineageos.org/c/LineageOS/hudson/+/242408|title=Prepare for 16.0|website=review.lineageos.org|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref>\n* On 1 March 2019, the first 16.0 official builds started to be available, following official announcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Changelog-22/|title=Changelog 22 - Pushing Pie, Bracing Builds and Careful Calculator|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> The 15.1 branch remains in active development, but without feature advancements.\n* On 28 February 2020, the 15.1 builds were stopped in preparation for the 17.1 release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/LineageOS/hudson/commit/4838aba0b3e9a71f0e7e07f9901c6ed81ea6fd80|title=RIP Oreo|website=github.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* On 1 April 2020, the first 17.1 builds started to be available, following official announcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Changelog-24/|title=Changelog 24|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The 16.0 builds are moved to a weekly cadence while the branch remains in active development, but without feature advancements.\n\nAll the released builds are signed with LineageOS' private keys.<ref name=\"build-prep\">{{cite web|url=http://lineageos.org/Update-and-Build-Prep/|title=Update & Build Prep|last=OS|first=Lineage|website=Lineageos.org|access-date=2017-01-21}}</ref>\n\nBuilds were released on a weekly basis until 12 November 2018, when the release cycle for devices has changed: the latest LineageOS branch is built daily, with devices receiving a \"nightly\" OTA update, while devices on the older branch are were moved to a weekly release cycle.<ref name=\"Release Cycle\">{{cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Changelog-21/|title=Changelog 21 - Nightlies Now, Improved Infrastructure and Precious Pie}}</ref>\n\n==Community==\nLineageOS allows the community to get involved with the development in various ways. [[Gerrit (software)|Gerrit]] is used for the code review process of both the operating system and the infrastructure.\n\nThe wiki, containing information regarding installation, support, and development of LineageOS, is also open to contributions through Gerrit. Other Lineage platforms include Crowdin for managing translations, [[GitLab|Gitlab Issues]] for bug tracking, and a stats page, which displays the number of active installations from users which opt-in to report this statistic. There is also an official [[Reddit|subreddit]], r/lineageos, and two [[Internet Relay Chat|IRC channels]] hosted on [[Freenode]] (''#lineageos'' and ''#lineageos-dev'').\n\nThe XDA Developers forums have been used by members of the Lineage community since the first inception of the software, many devices are left unsupported by official releases so community members develop their own Unofficial-ROMs that allow older phones to use Lineage. These unofficial releases are often bundled with software intended to aid the user's experience that would otherwise be unseen in an official release. They also come with known bugs and security issues that may not be seen in official releases.\n\nDuring August 2017 the LineageOS team held a Summer Survey<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lineageos.org/Summer-Survey/|title=Summer Survey|last=LineageOS|website=Lineageos.org|access-date=2017-10-25}}</ref> in which they asked users for feedback to improve the development of the operating system. The results were published<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lineageos.org/Summer-Survey-Results/|title=Summer Survey - Results|last=LineageOS|website=Lineageos.org|access-date=2017-10-25}}</ref> in October and, according to the team, they used the gathered data to improve the upcoming LineageOS 15 release. The second Summer Survey was conducted in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Summer-Survey-2/|title=Summer Survey 2 - Attack of the feedbacks|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org|access-date=2018-09-09}}</ref>\n\nAs a response to one of the main suggestions received during their first public survey, LineageOS launched a section on their blog titled \"LineageOS Engineering Blog\" where Lineage maintainers and developers can contribute articles discussing advanced technical information pertaining to Android development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Trust-me/|title=Trust me, I'm an engineer|date=12 June 2018|website=LineageOS|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nLineageOS is also known for posting a \"regularly irregular review\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lineageos.org/Changelog-13/|title=Changelog 13 - Wonderful Webviews, Pedantic Permissions and Disappearing Dates|last=LineageOS|website=Lineageos.org|access-date=2017-10-25}}</ref> on its blog in which the active development of the work is discussed.\n\n==Version history==\n{{See also|Android version history|CyanogenMod#History and development}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible\"\n|+\n|-\n! Version !! AOSP version\n!First build release date!! Last build release date\n!Support\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" {{Version|o|13.0}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 6.0.1<br />(Marshmallow)\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2016|12|20}} as CM<br />{{dts|format=dmy|2017|1|22}} as LOS\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2018|2|11}}\n|Unsupported\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" {{Version|o|14.1|show=}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 7.1.2 <br />(Nougat)\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2016|11|9}} as CM<br />{{dts|format=dmy|2017|1|22}} as LOS\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2019|2|24}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/LineageOS/hudson/commit/b8cf20218fd7676d7904152531e0f1cacead740f|title=Prepare for 16.0 \u00b7 LineageOS/hudson@b8cf202|website=GitHub|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref>\n|Unsupported\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" {{Version|o|15.1}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 8.1.0 <br />(Oreo)\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2018|2|26}}  \n|{{dts|format=dmy|2020|2|28}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/LineageOS/hudson/commit/4838aba0b3e9a71f0e7e07f9901c6ed81ea6fd80|title=RIP Oreo \u00b7 LineageOS/hudson@4838aba|website=Github|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n|Unsupported\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" {{Version|co|16.0}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 9.0.0 <br />(Pie)\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2019|3|1}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://review.lineageos.org/c/LineageOS/hudson/+/241918|title=The real lineage-16.0 ship commit}}</ref>\n| (Current)\n|Supported\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" {{Version|c|17.1}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 10 <br />\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2020|4|1}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Changelog-24|title=Changelog 24}}</ref>\n| (Current)\n|Supported\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" | <small>{{Version|l|show=111101}}</small>\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Preinstalled apps==\nLineageOS includes many essential and useful apps, but like its predecessor, CyanogenMod, it is free from unnecessary software often pre-installed by a phone's manufacturer or carrier that is considered to be [[bloatware]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://in.pcmag.com/lineage-os/112389/feature/how-to-install-lineage-os-on-your-smartphone |title=How to: Install Lineage OS on your smartphone |newspaper=In.pcmag.com |date=7 February 2017|author=Siddharth Chauhan|quote=As far as user interface goes, Lineage OS presents a clean and bloatware free stock Vanilla Android experience but still has some tricks up its sleeve. |accessdate= 20 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=carrieriq/>\n\n'''Current'''\n\n* AudioFX \u2013 Audio optimizer with presets to alter the listening experience.\n* Browser \u2013 A lightweight browser that relies on the System Webview, for low-end devices, also known as Jelly.\n* Calculator \u2013 which resembles a four-function calculator and offers some more advanced functions.\n* Calendar \u2013 Calendar functionality with Day, Week, Month, Year or Agenda views.\n* Camera \u2013 Dependent on device specification will take video or photos, including panoramic. It can also be used to read QR codes. This app is also known as Snap.\n* Clock \u2013 World clock, countdown timer, stopwatch and alarms.\n* Contacts \u2013 Phonebook for numbers and email addresses.\n* cLock - A weather widget.\n* Email \u2013 Email client that handles POP3, IMAP and Exchange.\n* Files \u2013 A simple file manager to move, copy and rename files on internal storage or SD card.\n* FlipFlap \u2013 An app for smart flip covers, only included on select devices.\n* FM Radio - An app for listening to FM radio broadcasts, included on devices with an FM tuner.\n* Gallery \u2013 Organize photos and videos into a timeline or albums for easy viewing.\n* Messaging \u2013An MMS/[[SMS]] messaging app.\n* Music \u2013 A simple music player, also known as Eleven.\n* Phone \u2013 for making calls: includes speed dial, phone number lookups and call blocking.\n* Recorder \u2013 A screen and/or sound recorder.\n* Trebuchet \u2013 A customizable launcher.\n* Terminal - A simple and standard terminal app.\n\n'''Former''' \n\n* Gello - A browser based on Chromium and developed by CyanogenMod. This app is now replaced by Jelly. \n* Yahoo Weather Provider - A weather provider\n* WeatherUnderground Weather Provider - A weather provider\n* Themes - Originally an app by itself, now integrated into the settings app.\n\nAlthough they are not included in LineageOS as such due to legal issues,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/09/24/google-hits-android-rom-modder-with-a-cease-and-desist-letter/|title=Google hits Android ROM modder with a cease-and-desist letter|work=Engadget|access-date=2017-10-25}}</ref> users can flash the normal Google apps, including the Google Play Store and Play Apps, with a [[Zip (file format)|Zip package]], usually referred to as ''gapps'', while installing LineageOS.\n\n==Unique features==\nLineageOS offers several features that [[Android (operating system)#AOSP|Android Open Source Project]] (AOSP) does not include. Some of these features are:\n\n==== Customization features ====\n\n* Button customization \u2013 Set custom location for buttons on the navigation bar, or enable on-screen buttons for devices with hardware buttons.\n* Custom Quick-Setting tiles \u2013 Quick Setting Tiles such as \"Caffeine\" preventing the device from sleeping, enabling/disabling Heads Up notifications, \"Ambient Display\" and \"ADB over network\" are present to easily toggle frequently accessed settings.\n* LiveDisplay \u2013 Adjust color temperature for the time of day.\n* Lock screen customization \u2013 The lock screen allows all sorts of customizations, including media cover art, a music visualizer, and double-tap to sleep.\n* Styles \u2013 Set a global dark or light theme mode and customize accent colors. This functionality can also be managed automatically by the system based on wallpaper or time of day (in line with LiveDisplay).\n* System Profiles \u2013 Enable or disable common settings based on the selected profile (For example, a \"Home\" profile and a \"Work\" profile). The profile can be selected either manually or through the use of a \"trigger\", such as upon connecting to a specific WiFi access point, connecting to a Bluetooth device, or tapping an [[Near-field communication|NFC]] tag.\n*Custom pattern sizes \u2013 In addition to Android's 3x3 pattern size, a 4x4, 5x5 or 6x6 size can be used.\n\n==== Security & privacy features ====\n\n* PIN scramble \u2013 For users securing their device with a [[Personal identification number|PIN]], the layout can be scrambled each time the device locks to make it difficult for people to figure out your lock by looking over your shoulder.\n* Privacy guard \u2013 Allow the user to fine-tune what permissions are granted to each application. For some permissions, it's possible to set a manual approval each time the permission is requested. It's also possible to find out how often apps use a specific permission. This feature was removed in the 17.1 branch in favor of an equivalent \"permission controller\" based on an hidden AOSP feature.\n* Protected Apps \u2013 Hide specific apps behind a secure lock. This works hand-in-hand with Trebuchet; the app's icon is removed from the launcher, and \"secure folders\" can be created to easily access these applications. A pattern is used to lock these apps.\n* Some \"sensitive numbers\", such as abuse support numbers, are not included in the call log for privacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Changelog-10/|title=Changelog 10 - Sensitive numbers and our CVE Tracker|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org}}</ref>\n* Trust - helps to keep the device secure and protects privacy.\n\n==== Developers & power user features ====\n\n* LineageSDK \u2013 a set of APIs for app developers to integrate their apps with LineageOS specific features such as System Profiles, Styles and Weather.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Introducing-the-LineageSDK/|title=Introducing the LineageSDK|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref>\n*Lineage Recovery - an AOSP-based recovery for devices with an A/B type system.\n* (Optional) Root \u2013 Permit apps to function with [[Superuser|root access]] to perform advanced tasks. This requires flashing from Recovery either LineageOS's root add-on or a third-party implementation such as Magisk.\n* Telephone call recorder, not available in all countries, due to legal restrictions.\n* Weather providers \u2013 Display the weather in widgets or apps using a weather provider. This functionality is not included by default; a weather provider must be downloaded from the LineageOS Downloads website. App developers can create both providers and consumers of weather data.\n\n==Trust interface==\nAs LineageOS evolved through development, the Trust interface was introduced for all the LineageOS 15.1 builds released since 12 June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/Trust-me/|title=Trust me, I'm an engineer|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org}}</ref> The interface can be found on supported devices under Security and Privacy tab under the Settings option, and enables the user to \"get an overview of the status of core security features and explanations on how to act to make sure the device is secure and the data is private\".\n\nAdditionally, while carrying out any action on the device, the trust icon is displayed, notifying the user that the action is safe.\n\n==Supported devices==\nThe number of devices supported by LineageOS increases with time, being 105 for v15.1 and v16 {{As of|2019|8|25|lc=y|df=US}}.<ref name=\"hudson build targets\"/><ref name=\"devices\">{{cite web|url= http://wiki.lineageos.org/devices/ |title= Devices |website= LineageOS Wiki |access-date= 2019-11-23 }}</ref> Official builds on currently supported development branches are labeled as either \"nightly\", \"weekly\", or \"monthly\". For the first two months of the project, parallel experimental builds were also produced, allowing in-place upgrades from previous CyanogenMod installations and easing migration to LineageOS.<ref name=\"devices\"/><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://download.lineageos.org|title=LineageOS Downloads|access-date=24 January 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126175103/https://download.lineageos.org/|archivedate=26 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://lineageos.org/Update-and-Build-Prep/|title=Update & Build Prep|date=20 January 2017|newspaper=LineageOS|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |last=Rigg |first=Jamie |date=24 January 2017 |title=The first builds of CyanogenMod successor LineageOS are out |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/01/24/cyanogenmod-lineageos/ |work=[[Engadget]] |accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism and reception  ==\n===2018 April Fools' prank ===\nLineageOS was criticized for a deceptive [[April Fools' Day|April Fool's]] prank included with some April 2018 builds.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.androidpolice.com/2018/04/05/dont-freak-lineageos-bad-late-april-fools-joke-latest-builds/|title=Don't freak out: LineageOS has a very bad and very late April Fools' joke in latest builds|date=2018-04-05|work=Android Police|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first week of April 2018 LineageOS released new builds with the \"LOSGenuine\" prank that informed unaware users of the software possibly being counterfeit via a persistent notification (which could not be disabled unless the user ran the following command in a root shell):\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"shell\">\nsetprop persist.lineage.nofool true \n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nWhen the notification was tapped, the software claimed that the device was \"uncertified\" and needed to mine \"LOSCoins\", which were a virtual currency and could not actually be spent. Affected builds also had a preinstalled \"Wallet\" app that showed the current balance of LOSCoins.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nMany users mistook the prank for actual [[malware]], and others reportedly found it to be in \"poor taste\". It was especially criticized for being too \"late\" for an April Fool's joke, since many users didn't receive the update until days later, making the jest less obvious. On 10 April 2018, LineageOS team director ''ciwrl'' issued an official apology for the deceptive prank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lineageos.org/An-April-Apology/|title=An April Apology|last=LineageOS|website=lineageos.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.androidpolice.com/2018/04/10/lineageos-apologises-late-bad-taste-april-fools-joke/|title=LineageOS apologizes for late and 'bad taste' April Fools' joke|date=2018-04-10|work=Android Police|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Forks==\n[[Replicant (operating system)|Replicant]] is a completely free software variant of LineageOS, with all kernel blobs and non-free drivers removed.\n\nAs a response to the refusal for several reasons of support for signature spoofing in official builds,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://review.lineageos.org/#/c/195284/|title=Gerrit Code Review|website=review.lineageos.org|access-date=2018-02-13}}</ref> a LineageOS fork with [[microG]]<ref name=\"microG\">\"[https://microg.org ''microG''] provides a free version of the set of APIs equivalent to Google\u2019s proprietary core libraries and applications.\"</ref> services included, known as \"LineageOS for microG\", was created. The project ships custom builds of LineageOS with the required patch and native [[F-Droid]] support, bundled with the MicroG project's [[free software|free]] re-implementation of proprietary [[Google mobile services|Gapps]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/LineageOS-Ableger-vermeidet-Google-Code-3879358.html|title=LineageOS-Ableger vermeidet Google-Code|first=heise|last=online|website=heise online}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gearallnews.com/what-is-microg-how-to-install-microg/|title=What is MicroG? How to Install MicroG?|date=26 November 2017|publisher=}}</ref> In other respects it follows upstream, shipping OTA updates every seven days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lineage.microg.org/|title=LineageOS for microG, FAQ}}</ref>\n\n[[/e/ (operating system)|/e/]] is a fork of LineageOS created by [[Ga\u00ebl Duval]] that is intended to be \"free from [[Google]]\". It replaces [[Google Play Services]] with MicroG, a [[free and open-source]] implementation of Google [[Application programming interface|APIs]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lemondeinformatique.fr/actualites/lire-eelo-l-os-mobile-open-source-de-gael-duval-sort-en-beta-72898.html|title=Eelo : l'OS mobile open source de Ga\u00ebl Duval sort en b\u00eata - Le Monde Informatique|last=Filippone|first=Dominique|date=September 19, 2018|website=LeMondeInformatique|language=fr|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Android rooting]]\n* [[Comparison of mobile operating systems]]\n* [[List of custom Android firmware]]\n* [[List of free and open-source Android applications]]\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.lineageos.org}}\n\n{{Android}}\n{{Linux-distro}}\n{{Mobile operating systems}}\n\n[[Category:Custom Android firmware]]\n[[Category:Embedded Linux distributions]]\n[[Category:Free mobile software]]\n[[Category:Software forks]]\n[[Category:Linux distributions without systemd]]\n[[Category:Android forks]]\n[[Category:2016 software]]\n", "name_user": "Darlade", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDevelopers & power user features", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LineageOS"}
{"title_page": "Tom McMahon (American football)", "text_new": "{{one source|date=January 2019}}\n\n{{short description|American football coach}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name        = Tom McMahon\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| current_team = Denver Broncos\n| position    = Special teams coordinator\n| birth_place = [[Helena, Montana]]\n| college     = [[Carroll College]]\n| pastcoaching   =\n* [[Carroll Fighting Saints football|Carroll College]] <br>Secondary (1992)\n* [[Bozeman High School]] <br>Assistant (1993)\n* [[Carroll Fighting Saints football|Carroll College]] <br>Secondary (1994)\n* [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]] <br>Graduate assistant (1995\u201397) <br>Linebackers/special teams (1998\u20132000) <br>Defensive line/recruiting coordinator (2001\u201305)\n* [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]] <br>Outside linebackers/special teams (2006)\n* [[Atlanta Falcons]] <br>Assistant special teams (2007\u201308)\n* [[Los Angeles Rams|St. Louis Rams]] <br>Special teams coordinator (2009\u201311)\n* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] <br>Special teams coordinator (2012)\n* [[Indianapolis Colts]] <br>Special teams coordinator (2013\u201317)\n* [[Denver Broncos]] <br>Special teams coordinator (2018\u2013present)\n| highlights  =\n}}\n'''Tom McMahon''' is an [[American football]] coach who is currently the [[special teams coordinator]] for the [[Denver Broncos]] of the [[National Football League]]. He previously held coaching positions for [[Carroll Fighting Saints football|Carroll College]], [[Bozeman High School]], [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]], and [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]], before starting his pro-career in 2007 as an assistant special teams coach for the [[Atlanta Falcons]]. He went on to become a special teams coordinator for the [[Los Angeles Rams|St. Louis Rams]], [[Kansas City Chiefs]], and [[Indianapolis Colts]], before joining the Broncos in 2018.<ref name=\"DEN\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.denverbroncos.com/team/coaches-roster/tom-mcmahon-1 |title=Tom McMahon |website=Denver Broncos |access-date=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McMahon, Tom}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos coaches]]\n[[Category:American football people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{one source|date=January 2019}}\n\n{{short description|American football coach}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name        = Tom McMahon\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| current_team = Denver Broncos\n| position    = Special teams coordinator\n| birth_place = [[Helena, Montana]]\n| college     = [[Carroll College]]\n| pastcoaching   =\n* [[Carroll Fighting Saints football|Carroll College]] <br>Secondary (1992)\n* [[Bozeman High School]] <br>Assistant (1993)\n* [[Carroll Fighting Saints football|Carroll College]] <br>Secondary (1994)\n* [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]] <br>Graduate assistant (1995\u201397) <br>Linebackers/special teams (1998\u20132000) <br>Defensive line/recruiting coordinator (2001\u201305)\n* [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]] <br>Outside linebackers/special teams (2006)\n* [[Atlanta Falcons]] <br>Assistant special teams (2007\u201308)\n* [[Los Angeles Rams|St. Louis Rams]] <br>Special teams coordinator (2009\u201311)\n* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] <br>Special teams coordinator (2012)\n* [[Indianapolis Colts]] <br>Special teams coordinator (2013-17)\n* [[Denver Broncos]] <br>Special teams coordinator (2018-present)\n| highlights  =\n}}\n'''Tom McMahon''' is an [[American football]] coach who is currently the [[special teams coordinator]] for the [[Denver Broncos]] of the [[National Football League]]. He previously held coaching positions for [[Carroll Fighting Saints football|Carroll College]], [[Bozeman High School]], [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]], and [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]], before starting his pro-career in 2007 as an assistant special teams coach for the [[Atlanta Falcons]]. He went on to become a special teams coordinator for the [[Los Angeles Rams|St. Louis Rams]], [[Kansas City Chiefs]], and [[Indianapolis Colts]], before joining the Broncos in 2018.<ref name=\"DEN\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.denverbroncos.com/team/coaches-roster/tom-mcmahon-1 |title=Tom McMahon |website=Denver Broncos |access-date=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McMahon, Tom}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos coaches]]\n[[Category:American football people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "FeverishAxe0", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInfobox NFL biography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_McMahon_(American_football)"}
{"title_page": "That Certain Feeling (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = That Certain Feeling\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]]\n| cover      = That Certain Feeling (album).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1968\n| recorded   = March 8, 1968\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Van Gelder Studio]], Englewood Cliffs, NJ\n| genre      = [[Jazz]]\n| length     = 41:09\n| label      = [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]]\n| producer   = [[Francis Wolff]]\n| chronology = [[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]]\n| prev_title = [[Got a Good Thing Goin']]\n| prev_year  = 1966\n| next_title = [[Boogaloo (John Patton album)|Boogaloo]]\n| next_year  = 1968\n}}\n\n'''''That Certain Feeling''''' is an album by American organist [[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]] recorded in 1968 and released on the [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]] label.<ref name=\"Blue Note discography\">[http://www.jazzdisco.org/blue-note-records/catalog-4200-series/#blp-4281 Blue Note Records discography] accessed November 5, 2010</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = ''[[AllMusic]]''\n| rev1Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/> \n}}\nThe [[AllMusic]] review by Stephen Thomas Erlewine awarded the album 3\u00bd stars and stated \"there are moments when everything comes together and it just cooks. And those are the moments that make ''That Certain Feeling'' worth a search\".<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{allmusic|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|class=album|id=mw0000880819|title=Big John Patton: ''That Certain Feeling'' \u2013 Review|accessdate= April 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll compositions by John Patton except where noted\n# \"String Bean\" - 5:42\n# \"I Want to Go Home\" - 8:36\n# \"Early A.M.\" - 7:17\n# \"Dirty Fingers\" - 6:09\n# \"Minor Swing\" - 6:38\n# \"Daddy James\" (Jimmy Watson) - 6:47\n:*Recorded at Rudy Van Gelder Studio, Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey on March 8, 1968.\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[John Patton (musician)|Big John Patton]] - [[electronic organ|organ]]\n*[[Junior Cook]] - [[tenor saxophone]]\n*[[Jimmy Ponder]] - [[guitar]]\n*[[Clifford Jarvis]] - [[drum kit|drums]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{John Patton (musician)}}\n\n[[Category:Blue Note Records albums]]\n[[Category:John Patton (musician) albums]]\n[[Category:1968 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Van Gelder Studio]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Alfred Lion]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = That Certain Feeling\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]]\n| cover      = That Certain Feeling (album).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1968\n| recorded   = March 8, 1968\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Van Gelder Studio]], Englewood Cliffs, NJ\n| genre      = [[Jazz]]\n| length     = 41:09\n| label      = [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]]\n| producer   = [[Francis Wolff]]\n| chronology = [[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]]\n| prev_title = [[Got a Good Thing Goin']]\n| prev_year  = 1966\n| next_title = [[Boogaloo (John Patton album)|Boogaloo]]\n| next_year  = 1968\n}}\n\n'''''That Certain Feeling''''' is an album by American organist [[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]] recorded in 1968 and released on the [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]] label.<ref name=\"Blue Note discography\">[http://www.jazzdisco.org/blue-note-records/catalog-4200-series/#blp-4281 Blue Note Records discography] accessed November 5, 2010</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = ''[[Allmusic]]''\n| rev1Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/> \n}}\nThe [[Allmusic]] review by Stephen Thomas Erlewine awarded the album 3\u00bd stars and stated \"there are moments when everything comes together and it just cooks. And those are the moments that make ''That Certain Feeling'' worth a search\".<ref name=\"Allmusic\">Erlewine, S. T. [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=that-certain-feeling-r155808|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic Review] accessed November 5, 2010</ref>\n\n==Track list